WEBVTT

00:06.006 --> 00:06.632
<i>[exciting music]</i>

00:06.632 --> 00:08.759
<i>[exciting music]</i>

00:08.759 --> 00:13.889
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:15.098 --> 00:18.644
<i>‐ My name's Richey Crew.</i>
<i>I love forging knives.</i>

00:18.644 --> 00:20.979
It's like playing with Play‐Doh
when you was a kid.

00:20.979 --> 00:23.815
<i>You can mold it</i>
<i>to be many things.</i>

00:23.815 --> 00:25.359
<i>But it has to go</i>
<i>through the fire.</i>

00:25.359 --> 00:26.818
Human beings are the same way.

00:26.818 --> 00:28.862
We have to go
through fires in life

00:28.862 --> 00:31.657
to be molded into
what we need to be.

00:32.908 --> 00:34.660
<i>‐ My name's Elijah Williams.</i>
<i>I am really blessed</i>

00:34.660 --> 00:37.204
to be able to be
a full‐time bladesmith

00:37.204 --> 00:39.039
<i>and a stay‐at‐home dad.</i>

00:39.039 --> 00:40.874
<i>The hardest part</i>
<i>is finding the time</i>

00:40.874 --> 00:43.710
<i>to dedicate specifically</i>
<i>to that as a job.</i>

00:43.710 --> 00:45.379
You're like, "Okay, I'm done
with the diaper changes.

00:45.379 --> 00:46.755
I got to go make a knife now."

00:47.714 --> 00:49.258
<i>‐ My name is Austin Hensley,</i>

00:49.258 --> 00:50.384
<i>and I'm from Roswell,</i>
<i>New Mexico.</i>

00:50.384 --> 00:53.595
<i>I am a firefighter/EMT.</i>

00:53.595 --> 00:55.597
As a firefighter,
I do deal with a lot of stress

00:55.597 --> 00:57.391
and a lot of pressure,
you know, there‐‐

00:57.391 --> 00:59.309
<i>People's lives on the line.</i>
<i>I can't choke up.</i>

00:59.309 --> 01:02.020
I feel like that will help me
here in this competition.

01:02.020 --> 01:04.314
<i>‐ My name is Dan Linton.</i>
<i>Bladesmithing for me</i>

01:04.314 --> 01:06.441
is a therapeutic process.

01:06.441 --> 01:09.152
<i>I had a lot of trials</i>
<i>and stuff I struggle with.</i>

01:09.152 --> 01:11.029
Eventually, I got past them.

01:11.029 --> 01:13.907
<i>But I had this massive</i>
<i>amount of energy.</i>

01:13.907 --> 01:15.701
So I make knives,
'cause it's something

01:15.701 --> 01:18.704
I can focus my energy into.

01:19.705 --> 01:23.417
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:23.417 --> 01:25.419
Each of you has come here
to engage in three rounds

01:25.419 --> 01:28.422
of timed edged weapon‐making
competition,

01:28.422 --> 01:30.966
specifically designed
to test every aspect

01:30.966 --> 01:32.759
of your bladesmithing
capabilities,

01:32.759 --> 01:35.095
all in front of a panel
of expert judges

01:35.095 --> 01:37.139
who's gonna tell us
which of you

01:37.139 --> 01:38.557
is our next
"Forged in Fire" champion,

01:38.557 --> 01:41.893
leaving here with a check
for $10,000.

01:41.893 --> 01:46.898
Up first,
ABS Mastersmith J. Neilson.

01:46.898 --> 01:49.276
Next, Historic Weapons
Recreation Specialist

01:49.276 --> 01:50.902
David Baker.

01:50.902 --> 01:54.614
And last, Edged Weapon
Specialist Doug Marcaida.

01:54.614 --> 01:56.575
Gentlemen, I know
that cloth‐draped items

01:56.575 --> 01:58.118
in the middle of this Forge
make you nervous,

01:58.118 --> 02:00.454
so let's make you feel
more comfortable.

02:00.454 --> 02:03.332
<i>[intense musical buildup]</i>

02:03.332 --> 02:06.043
<i>[dramatic musical sting]</i>

02:06.043 --> 02:10.130
What you see here is a
Fairbairn‐Sykes fighting knife.

02:10.130 --> 02:12.799
<i>This iconic knife</i>
<i>is the deadly melee weapon</i>

02:12.799 --> 02:15.969
<i>of British commanders,</i>
<i>dating back to World War II.</i>

02:15.969 --> 02:18.013
<i>Designed by</i>
<i>William Ewart Fairbairn</i>

02:18.013 --> 02:19.598
<i>and Eric Anthony Sykes,</i>

02:19.598 --> 02:21.558
<i>the sleek knife</i>
<i>was often employed</i>

02:21.558 --> 02:23.602
<i>in silent and surprise</i>
<i>attacks on enemies</i>

02:23.602 --> 02:26.063
<i>and had the ability</i>
<i>to quickly penetrate deep</i>

02:26.063 --> 02:28.190
<i>into vital areas</i>
<i>of the body.</i>

02:28.190 --> 02:30.108
Now...

02:30.108 --> 02:31.568
what, pray tell,

02:31.568 --> 02:34.655
are we gonna forge
these blades out of?

02:34.655 --> 02:37.157
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

02:37.157 --> 02:39.534
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:39.534 --> 02:44.414
These are rounds of W1 steel
in varying diameters.

02:44.414 --> 02:48.669
Your challenge is to take three
different diameters of W1 steel

02:48.669 --> 02:51.505
and forge weld them
together into a billet

02:51.505 --> 02:54.883
from which you will make
your F‐S fighting knife.

02:54.883 --> 02:56.718
<i>This knife has</i>
<i>a diamond cross‐section</i>

02:56.718 --> 02:58.637
<i>and central ridge</i>
<i>and a through tang.</i>

02:58.637 --> 03:00.097
<i>Your blade length</i>
<i>must be between</i>

03:00.097 --> 03:01.598
<i>8 and 10 inches in length</i>

03:01.598 --> 03:04.601
<i>and must not exceed</i>
<i>22 inches.</i>

03:04.601 --> 03:07.020
<i>‐ Daggers are really tough.</i>
<i>You got the four bevels</i>

03:07.020 --> 03:09.272
<i>and everything's got</i>
<i>to be symmetrical</i>

03:09.272 --> 03:11.316
<i>and the edge geometry has got</i>
<i>to be correct on each side.</i>

03:11.316 --> 03:13.276
This isn't gonna be very easy.

03:13.276 --> 03:16.029
‐ In the second round, you'll
attach handles to those blades,

03:16.029 --> 03:18.407
turning them into
fully functional daggers

03:18.407 --> 03:21.451
that will be tested for
strength and durability

03:21.451 --> 03:23.078
in a gas can stab,

03:23.078 --> 03:24.454
and for edge retention,

03:24.454 --> 03:27.624
a Kevlar‐reinforced
sandbag slice.

03:27.624 --> 03:29.167
When the time runs out
on the clock

03:29.167 --> 03:31.795
and the judges have taken
a look at your work,

03:31.795 --> 03:33.922
one of you will have
to surrender your blade

03:33.922 --> 03:35.674
and leave The Forge.

03:35.674 --> 03:38.593
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your three hours starts now.

03:38.593 --> 03:40.053
<i>[rock music]</i>

03:40.053 --> 03:42.973
We actually have
six different diameters

03:42.973 --> 03:45.100
of W1 steel,

03:45.100 --> 03:47.519
and our four bladesmiths
have to choose

03:47.519 --> 03:50.147
three different diameters
each to use.

03:50.147 --> 03:54.234
The complication is materials
management, time management,

03:54.234 --> 03:56.570
and then they have
to try to replicate

03:56.570 --> 03:58.447
that shape that's out there.

03:58.447 --> 04:02.492
‐ You need to be able to look
at a knife and duplicate it.

04:02.492 --> 04:04.661
It's an important
skill to develop

04:04.661 --> 04:06.246
if you're a bladesmith.

04:06.246 --> 04:09.082
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:09.082 --> 04:11.334
‐ I go and grab three of
the smaller pieces of rod.

04:11.334 --> 04:14.588
I cut them down a little bit
and weld them together.

04:14.588 --> 04:17.424
‐ Having that gap in the center
is gonna be a problem.

04:17.424 --> 04:19.801
He doesn't fill that gap in,
it could cause an issue.

04:19.801 --> 04:22.429
<i>‐ Well, the three different</i>
<i>rods are different diameters.</i>

04:22.429 --> 04:24.473
<i>That means they're gonna heat</i>
<i>differently in the forge,</i>

04:24.473 --> 04:27.184
so you're gonna get one too hot
while one is not hot enough.

04:27.184 --> 04:30.896
That just makes it
very, very complex.

04:30.896 --> 04:33.857
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

04:33.857 --> 04:35.275
‐ Whoa!
‐ Oh!

04:35.275 --> 04:37.068
‐ It looks like
that opened up on him.

04:37.068 --> 04:39.571
‐ All right.
<i>I decide to just stop it</i>

04:39.571 --> 04:42.282
and start over again,
try a new strategy.

04:42.282 --> 04:44.242
I just tried to do a weld
and it was blowing out,

04:44.242 --> 04:46.077
so I'm gonna flatten these

04:46.077 --> 04:47.454
<i>and forge weld</i>
<i>all three of them together.</i>

04:47.454 --> 04:48.747
I don't know
what I was thinking.

04:48.747 --> 04:50.791
I'm losing my mind.

04:50.791 --> 04:52.334
<i>I'm that kinda person</i>
<i>that sees an obstacle</i>

04:52.334 --> 04:55.420
<i>and can't wait to kick</i>
<i>a hole in it.</i>

04:56.505 --> 04:58.465
‐ I'm gonna go with the three
biggest diameters

04:58.465 --> 05:00.801
<i>that they got out there</i>
<i>so I have enough steel.</i>

05:00.801 --> 05:02.761
‐ Austin, he cut up
three discs,

05:02.761 --> 05:05.555
stacked them to weld 'em
like a wedding cake.

05:05.555 --> 05:08.016
It's all W1, a simple steel
to forge weld together

05:08.016 --> 05:10.227
and then draw your blade out
from there, quick and easy.

05:10.227 --> 05:11.812
He's done almost everything

05:11.812 --> 05:13.522
just the way
I would have done it.

05:13.522 --> 05:15.106
<i>‐ I don't have to put my steel</i>
<i>in the fire</i>

05:15.106 --> 05:17.108
<i>forge it out,</i>
<i>then clean it up</i>

05:17.108 --> 05:18.693
if I just get right
to forge welding.

05:18.693 --> 05:21.029
<i>I've never done a forge weld</i>
<i>like this,</i>

05:21.029 --> 05:23.073
so I'm gonna be very cautious.

05:23.073 --> 05:25.617
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:25.617 --> 05:27.494
<i>‐ Some of the stock they have</i>
<i>out there is big enough</i>

05:27.494 --> 05:31.081
to make a fricking hammer,
so I'm not gonna be using that.

05:31.081 --> 05:33.416
I'm gonna take
some of the smaller pieces

05:33.416 --> 05:37.087
<i>and start flattening</i>
<i>the three separate pieces out</i>

05:37.087 --> 05:39.172
until they're relatively
the same thickness

05:39.172 --> 05:42.467
that I can then put together
and do a forge weld.

05:42.467 --> 05:46.388
‐ So we got Elijah, Richey,
and Dan

05:46.388 --> 05:49.683
drawing out full bars of steel.

05:49.683 --> 05:51.226
But if you just cut the discs
off and forge weld 'em

05:51.226 --> 05:53.395
in one shot,
it would save you a lot work.

05:55.146 --> 05:57.899
<i>[rock music]</i>

05:57.899 --> 05:59.985
‐ Now that I've got all three
of my billets flat,

05:59.985 --> 06:02.070
<i>I'm bringing it up</i>
<i>to heat now.</i>

06:02.070 --> 06:04.656
Forgot my hat.
Can't work without my hat.

06:04.656 --> 06:06.283
[chuckles]

06:06.283 --> 06:08.994
‐ Richey's at the point
of overheating his steel.

06:08.994 --> 06:13.123
‐ I'm trying to set my weld,
and I shifted my top layer.

06:13.123 --> 06:15.125
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:15.125 --> 06:18.211
<i>Got to get those welds set</i>
<i>good to be able to turn it up</i>

06:18.211 --> 06:20.297
and square that billet back up.

06:20.297 --> 06:22.299
‐ The design of that dagger,

06:22.299 --> 06:25.719
it tapers down continuously
from the guard.

06:25.719 --> 06:27.304
You got to have
your edge centered,

06:27.304 --> 06:29.598
your plunge grinds even,
your centerline even,

06:29.598 --> 06:31.850
all four of those planes even

06:31.850 --> 06:33.810
so you don't have a twist
going down your blade.

06:33.810 --> 06:35.312
There's so many different
things

06:35.312 --> 06:37.022
you got to pay attention to
all at once.

06:37.022 --> 06:39.774
‐ So I'm gonna keep my heat up
and get my weld set good

06:39.774 --> 06:41.651
and then square my billet.

06:41.651 --> 06:44.404
I forgot to look at the clock.
Where is it at? There it is.

06:44.404 --> 06:47.824
<i>I ain't even got a calendar</i>
<i>in my shop, much less a clock.</i>

06:47.824 --> 06:50.160
So, uh, this is a challenge.
[laughs]

06:50.160 --> 06:53.163
‐ Bladesmiths,
one hour has elapsed!

06:53.163 --> 06:55.373
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:55.373 --> 06:57.125
‐ My little wedding cake
paid off.

06:57.125 --> 06:59.961
Doing pretty good.
I think I got one solid piece.

06:59.961 --> 07:03.715
Makes me feel happy.
Now I can forge it to shape.

07:03.715 --> 07:05.592
<i>I watched some</i>
<i>J. Neilson videos,</i>

07:05.592 --> 07:09.387
and he's done some daggers,
and now he's here watching me.

07:09.387 --> 07:11.931
<i>You know, I'm just afraid he's</i>
<i>gonna come out and be like,</i>

07:11.931 --> 07:13.683
"Oh, man, what in the world‐‐"

07:16.102 --> 07:18.063
<i>[rock music]</i>

07:18.063 --> 07:22.025
‐ I have a nice good billet
to make a knife out of.

07:22.025 --> 07:24.694
<i>I have never made anything</i>
<i>like this before,</i>

07:24.694 --> 07:27.072
so I'm really excited to see
how this comes out.

07:27.072 --> 07:29.824
‐ You got that very aggressive
tapered tip.

07:29.824 --> 07:32.911
And we're stabbing
into gasoline cans.

07:32.911 --> 07:34.621
If that tip's thick,
it's not gonna penetrate.

07:34.621 --> 07:36.581
If it doesn't penetrate,
it's not a dagger.

07:36.581 --> 07:37.999
<i>‐ Got to take some</i>
<i>off the tang</i>

07:37.999 --> 07:39.459
<i>and a little bit</i>
<i>off the blade,</i>

07:39.459 --> 07:40.794
<i>then it'll be time</i>
<i>for heat treat,</i>

07:40.794 --> 07:42.754
<i>then it's time to finish.</i>

07:42.754 --> 07:44.714
Only thing I'm worried about
is how good it'll look,

07:44.714 --> 07:46.966
which I think
that's pretty good.

07:46.966 --> 07:49.260
‐ I'm heating my steel up
to welding temperature

07:49.260 --> 07:52.305
with flux on it.
I'm doing a weld pass

07:52.305 --> 07:54.641
with a hammer
and repeating the process.

07:54.641 --> 07:57.519
I just want to make sure that
weld is good before I move on.

07:57.519 --> 08:01.815
‐ I'm getting really worried
about Elijah.

08:01.815 --> 08:04.442
I see flux, heat,
hammer, brush‐‐

08:04.442 --> 08:07.904
flux, heat, hammer, brush‐‐

08:07.904 --> 08:11.241
and he's just not
making any progress.

08:11.241 --> 08:13.493
‐ I'm spending
a little more time

08:13.493 --> 08:15.578
than I would like to
on the forge weld,

08:15.578 --> 08:20.834
<i>but I want to make sure that</i>
<i>weld is good before I move on.</i>

08:20.834 --> 08:22.794
‐ These welds
should already be set.

08:22.794 --> 08:24.295
‐ Not set now,
they're not gonna be.

08:24.295 --> 08:26.423
‐ Yeah, no.
<i>‐ Clock's running out,</i>

08:26.423 --> 08:28.133
and I still have
a lot of work to do.

08:28.133 --> 08:29.634
‐ Now it's time to panic.

08:32.929 --> 08:36.141
time than I would like to
<i>[d</i>
<i>‐ I'm spending a lie</i>

08:36.141 --> 08:39.018
on the forge weld.
I think one of my weaknesses

08:39.018 --> 08:41.521
might be being
a little too meticulous.

08:41.521 --> 08:43.356
<i>I don't want to have failure,</i>

08:43.356 --> 08:46.359
but I need to keep it within
the time parameters as well.

08:46.359 --> 08:49.279
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:49.279 --> 08:53.199
‐ I believe I got my weld set.
I believe they are rock solid.

08:53.199 --> 08:56.870
I almost shaped my point,
got my general profile out.

08:56.870 --> 08:59.372
‐ Richey's blade has more
of that spear point.

08:59.372 --> 09:01.207
That's not what
we're looking for.

09:01.207 --> 09:04.878
We want something that tapers
all the way to the tip.

09:04.878 --> 09:07.547
‐ There is no reason
that you shouldn't know

09:07.547 --> 09:10.550
what that shape
of that blade should be.

09:10.550 --> 09:12.677
We have an F‐S blade
right out there.

09:12.677 --> 09:16.056
This particular challenge
is about a specific blade.

09:16.056 --> 09:18.683
I'd like to see them test
their skills

09:18.683 --> 09:21.227
to make something
that we're asking for.

09:21.227 --> 09:23.730
<i>‐ Shaping this thing up,</i>
<i>and you get one side right</i>

09:23.730 --> 09:25.106
and you look over
on the other side

09:25.106 --> 09:26.608
and you went too far,

09:26.608 --> 09:28.943
so you got to go back
to match those sides up.

09:28.943 --> 09:33.073
‐ I mean, that symmetry
is crucial to correct function.

09:33.073 --> 09:35.617
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:35.617 --> 09:39.746
‐ The question is who's gonna
be playing the smart bet

09:39.746 --> 09:41.998
and quenching before
they go to the grinder?

09:41.998 --> 09:44.167
That's a smart thing to do
with a dagger.

09:44.167 --> 09:45.794
‐ Now why is it smarter
to do that

09:45.794 --> 09:47.587
with a dagger
than any other blade?

09:47.587 --> 09:49.923
‐ One of the biggest issues
you see with daggers

09:49.923 --> 09:52.092
is you look down it
from the tip,

09:52.092 --> 09:54.260
and you're supposed to have
that diamond profile,

09:54.260 --> 09:56.096
but it's twisted.

09:56.096 --> 09:58.431
If your grinds aren't even,
you got those four grinds,

09:58.431 --> 10:00.433
it's gonna cool differently.

10:00.433 --> 10:01.768
It'll cool
at different temperatures,

10:01.768 --> 10:03.603
and the cooling metal
will move.

10:03.603 --> 10:06.731
So you could end up with
a skewer instead of a dagger.

10:06.731 --> 10:08.775
‐ Better to quench it
while it's thick

10:08.775 --> 10:11.319
and then grind it to shape.

10:11.319 --> 10:14.656
And it looks like Dan
is over at the fan.

10:14.656 --> 10:16.741
He's doing some
thermocycling.

10:16.741 --> 10:19.160
<i>‐ I'm gonna heat it up and let</i>
<i>it cool to room temperature.</i>

10:19.160 --> 10:21.329
That should align
the carbon molecules

10:21.329 --> 10:24.207
and take any of the stress
out of the blade.

10:24.207 --> 10:26.501
<i>[rock music]</i>

10:26.501 --> 10:29.671
<i>I am so relieved there isn't</i>
<i>a crack, there's isn't a warp.</i>

10:29.671 --> 10:31.256
<i>It's just a beautiful blade</i>

10:31.256 --> 10:34.551
that I'm gonna be able
to grind into shape.

10:34.551 --> 10:36.469
<i>[rock music]</i>

10:36.469 --> 10:38.680
<i>‐ I've got my blade profile.</i>

10:38.680 --> 10:40.140
I'm gonna try and set up
for round two.

10:40.140 --> 10:41.808
‐ Looks like...

10:41.808 --> 10:44.686
he's gonna thread
that tang already.

10:44.686 --> 10:46.646
‐ This is getting ahead
of yourself.

10:46.646 --> 10:48.815
‐ Those threads that he's
putting in there right now

10:48.815 --> 10:51.985
are gonna be so easy
to rip, clog, crush,

10:51.985 --> 10:53.319
and mess up...

10:53.319 --> 10:54.654
‐ Exactly!
‐ During this process.

10:54.654 --> 10:56.489
‐ We're gonna make
a through tang

10:56.489 --> 10:58.491
and we might as well make it
a threaded on through tang,

10:58.491 --> 11:00.451
make it a real
strong construction.

11:00.451 --> 11:02.328
<i>I don't really trust</i>
<i>through tang,</i>

11:02.328 --> 11:04.664
now it's not a thread tang.

11:04.664 --> 11:07.667
‐ Now, the F‐S fighting knife
weighs less than 1/2 pound.

11:07.667 --> 11:10.545
‐ And that's why the heat treat
is gonna be so crucial.

11:10.545 --> 11:12.338
Don't overheat it,
don't underheat it.

11:12.338 --> 11:15.300
Get it just right. Get that
nice fine grain structure.

11:15.300 --> 11:18.011
‐ Austin quenches his blade.

11:18.011 --> 11:19.846
<i>‐ I've got a hardened blade.</i>

11:19.846 --> 11:21.639
I've got my threaded
through tang.

11:21.639 --> 11:22.974
I'm feeling pretty good.

11:22.974 --> 11:26.060
‐ Bladesmiths,
two hours has elapsed!

11:26.060 --> 11:27.729
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:27.729 --> 11:29.230
‐ The forge weld
is finally good,

11:29.230 --> 11:30.982
and I'm forging it out

11:30.982 --> 11:33.067
<i>into roughly the shape</i>
<i>that it needs to be.</i>

11:33.067 --> 11:35.195
‐ At least now it looks like
he's trusting his weld.

11:35.195 --> 11:39.032
<i>‐ The shape of this knife</i>
<i>is designed for penetration.</i>

11:39.032 --> 11:40.658
<i>And because of that,</i>

11:40.658 --> 11:44.245
it's got some very
gradual tapers to the blade.

11:44.245 --> 11:47.040
‐ It's all about the thrusting.
It's got edges to slash.

11:47.040 --> 11:49.083
But the blade itself,
it's not very big.

11:49.083 --> 11:51.044
So with a lighter edge
for that,

11:51.044 --> 11:54.047
the slash pretty much
complements the killing thrust.

11:54.047 --> 11:57.258
<i>‐ I have to, uh, just finish</i>
<i>this blade out in time.</i>

11:57.258 --> 12:00.887
That's what I'm really
trying to focus on here.

12:02.513 --> 12:03.932
‐ I'm about to quench.

12:03.932 --> 12:06.392
Everything's looking
straight and good.

12:06.392 --> 12:09.395
<i>[rock music]</i>

12:09.395 --> 12:11.606
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:11.606 --> 12:13.691
<i>I've got my blade hardened,</i>

12:13.691 --> 12:14.901
and I'm real comfortable
with it.

12:14.901 --> 12:16.736
<i>It looks good.</i>

12:16.736 --> 12:20.406
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:20.406 --> 12:23.243
‐ I've got a hardened blade.
I've got the parameters in.

12:23.243 --> 12:25.745
<i>Now it's kind of just making</i>
<i>those bevels just right.</i>

12:25.745 --> 12:27.580
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:27.580 --> 12:29.582
<i>Daggers‐‐one of the reasons</i>
<i>I don't really like them</i>

12:29.582 --> 12:31.626
<i>is because you got</i>
<i>four bevels.</i>

12:31.626 --> 12:34.420
This particular bevel's
pretty hard to grind in

12:34.420 --> 12:36.756
<i>just because everything's</i>
<i>got to be even,</i>

12:36.756 --> 12:38.466
<i>and then, on the other side,</i>

12:38.466 --> 12:40.260
<i>everything's</i>
<i>got to be even there.</i>

12:40.260 --> 12:42.095
That's what makes these things
so dang hard.

12:42.095 --> 12:43.930
‐ One thing these smiths

12:43.930 --> 12:46.474
are going to have to be
careful of in that final grind

12:46.474 --> 12:49.102
is not to overheat that steel
as they draw that down.

12:49.102 --> 12:50.603
‐ It's gotta be strong.

12:50.603 --> 12:53.648
I mean, this is a very,
very lean tip.

12:53.648 --> 12:57.151
They could snap off inside
of one of those gas cans.

12:57.151 --> 12:59.028
<i>‐ Got my bevels in.</i>

12:59.028 --> 13:01.281
Now it looks good,
and it should perform.

13:01.281 --> 13:03.283
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:03.283 --> 13:05.952
‐ Bladesmiths, 30 minutes!

13:05.952 --> 13:08.204
<i>[intense music]</i>

13:08.204 --> 13:11.124
<i>‐ You're shaping</i>
<i>four sides of a knife</i>

13:11.124 --> 13:13.293
<i>to the exact same degree.</i>

13:13.293 --> 13:15.837
This is becoming the hardest
part of the challenge.

13:15.837 --> 13:18.047
‐ These guys have to be
wondering,

13:18.047 --> 13:22.844
does their blade closely enough
match the example?

13:22.844 --> 13:24.971
‐ It's definitely
more difficult to recreate

13:24.971 --> 13:27.473
than just create from scratch.

13:27.473 --> 13:29.058
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:29.058 --> 13:30.643
‐ Nothing is lining up.

13:30.643 --> 13:32.478
‐ I'm a little worried
that Dan doesn't know

13:32.478 --> 13:37.358
exactly how to get
the bevels into this dagger.

13:37.358 --> 13:39.652
‐ I definitely know
what I want this to be,

13:39.652 --> 13:42.280
<i>but I'm struggling</i>
<i>making it happen.</i>

13:42.280 --> 13:43.865
‐ Having a blade that's got
that profile,

13:43.865 --> 13:46.325
<i>both, you know,</i>
<i>a triangle going this way</i>

13:46.325 --> 13:48.536
<i>and a triangle going this way</i>
<i>with a medial ridge</i>

13:48.536 --> 13:49.996
<i>is a very difficult</i>
<i>thing to grind</i>

13:49.996 --> 13:51.831
if you're not used to
doing it.

13:51.831 --> 13:55.626
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:55.626 --> 13:57.336
‐ Elijah ground his blade
to shape,

13:57.336 --> 13:58.838
but he probably
should have quenched it

13:58.838 --> 14:00.339
before doing
that much grinding.

14:00.339 --> 14:02.008
‐ If Elijah has a problem,

14:02.008 --> 14:03.843
he has a warp or [indistinct]
in his blade,

14:03.843 --> 14:05.928
he's gonna have
a really hard time fixing that.

14:06.971 --> 14:08.890
<i>‐ Just hoping to get</i>
<i>this blade heat‐treated</i>

14:08.890 --> 14:11.059
and back on the grinder
so I can get these bevels

14:11.059 --> 14:14.228
finished up
before the clock runs out.

14:15.229 --> 14:17.732
‐ Elijah has, uh,
has quenched.

14:17.732 --> 14:20.193
‐ It's got a little bit
of a warp to it.

14:20.193 --> 14:22.695
<i>I'm bending it really,</i>
<i>really carefully.</i>

14:22.695 --> 14:24.697
<i>I think I've got the warp</i>
<i>out of the blade.</i>

14:24.697 --> 14:28.326
It's not perfect, but I can't
spend any more time on that.

14:28.326 --> 14:30.036
<i>I gotta clean these bevels</i>
<i>up a little more,</i>

14:30.036 --> 14:33.081
get my edge geometry down

14:33.081 --> 14:37.418
and make this blade
as nice as I can.

14:37.418 --> 14:39.921
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:39.921 --> 14:42.340
<i>‐ Man, I'm nearly finished.</i>
<i>Don't let me mess up now.</i>

14:42.340 --> 14:44.509
[laughing]

14:46.094 --> 14:48.679
‐ Richey's blade is a little
bit on the wider side...

14:48.679 --> 14:50.056
‐ Then it drops
the last 2 inches

14:50.056 --> 14:53.101
as opposed to tapering
to a fine point.

14:53.101 --> 14:56.229
‐ But that's all something that
can be worked out grinding it.

14:56.229 --> 14:58.856
<i>‐ Right now, I'm thinking,</i>
<i>my blade's too wide,</i>

14:58.856 --> 15:02.735
my profile is a little steep.
Not a lot of time on the clock.

15:02.735 --> 15:05.238
Probably not gonna have time
to get it fixed.

15:06.697 --> 15:09.158
‐ Five, four,

15:09.158 --> 15:12.245
three, two, one!

15:12.245 --> 15:14.914
Bladesmiths, shut down
your machines, drop your tools.

15:14.914 --> 15:18.376
This first round of smithing
competition is over.

15:20.545 --> 15:22.964
‐ This is definitely not the
blade design I had in my head.

15:22.964 --> 15:24.924
<i>I'm really expecting</i>
<i>some criticism.</i>

15:24.924 --> 15:26.926
<i>But that's the great thing</i>
<i>about this competition is</i>

15:26.926 --> 15:29.929
one person wins and the other
three really learn something.

15:29.929 --> 15:32.098
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

15:32.098 --> 15:34.475
‐ All right, bladesmiths.
In this first round

15:34.475 --> 15:36.435
of competition,
each of you was to have made

15:36.435 --> 15:39.814
an F‐S fighting knife
style blade.

15:39.814 --> 15:42.108
Now it's time for the judges

15:42.108 --> 15:43.901
to take a closer
look at your work.

15:43.901 --> 15:45.319
Richey, you're up first.

15:45.319 --> 15:47.613
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:47.613 --> 15:51.284
‐ Hi, Richey.
Your profile's close.

15:51.284 --> 15:52.410
<i>You know, it's a little</i>
<i>more rounded here</i>

15:52.410 --> 15:54.120
<i>than we have on our example.</i>

15:54.120 --> 15:56.789
You've also got a bit of
a twist going down your blade

15:56.789 --> 16:00.418
but left enough meat on here
that that can be fixed.

16:00.418 --> 16:02.461
So overall,
you're on the way.

16:02.461 --> 16:04.422
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:04.422 --> 16:05.840
‐ Elijah, you're up.

16:05.840 --> 16:08.467
Please present your blade
to the judges.

16:08.467 --> 16:11.137
‐ Elijah, you got a pretty good
warp in that blade.

16:11.137 --> 16:13.472
It's certainly fixable,
but, you know,

16:13.472 --> 16:15.099
when you're
dealing with a dagger,

16:15.099 --> 16:16.934
not quite as easy
to fix a warp as it is

16:16.934 --> 16:19.312
when you've got that
spinal blade to work with.

16:19.312 --> 16:21.022
I love the shape.

16:21.022 --> 16:22.190
I love the grinds
that you got on here.

16:22.190 --> 16:24.901
Well on your way.

16:24.901 --> 16:27.320
‐ All right, Austin,
you're up.

16:27.320 --> 16:28.863
<i>‐ I like this, Austin.</i>

16:28.863 --> 16:30.698
<i>You still got a lot of meat</i>
<i>on here,</i>

16:30.698 --> 16:32.491
and there's a lot
in your tang as well.

16:32.491 --> 16:34.619
So you're probably gonna need
to reduce that down some.

16:34.619 --> 16:36.787
I like the way you took
your three pieces

16:36.787 --> 16:39.207
and forge welded them together.
Overall, good job.

16:39.207 --> 16:41.792
‐ Thank you.
‐ All right, Dan,

16:41.792 --> 16:45.171
you may present your work
to the judges.

16:45.171 --> 16:47.340
<i>‐ All right, Dan, this is what</i>
<i>I like about your blade.</i>

16:47.340 --> 16:49.008
<i>Definitely, it's got the point</i>
<i>in there like a spear</i>

16:49.008 --> 16:50.384
that you can attack with.

16:50.384 --> 16:53.346
Unfortunately,
there are a lot of things

16:53.346 --> 16:55.514
that we're asking for here
that aren't met here.

16:55.514 --> 16:57.350
<i>It doesn't taper‐‐</i>
<i>it flares out here,</i>

16:57.350 --> 16:58.601
<i>and then it comes down.</i>

16:58.601 --> 17:00.394
It doesn't have
a central ridge.

17:00.394 --> 17:02.563
You can make a blade.

17:02.563 --> 17:04.690
It's just not the one
we're asking for.

17:04.690 --> 17:07.818
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:07.818 --> 17:10.905
‐ Bladesmiths, the judges
made their final decision.

17:10.905 --> 17:12.823
The bladesmith leaving
The Forge is...

17:12.823 --> 17:15.201
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

17:15.201 --> 17:18.537
Dan. Your blade
didn't make the cut.

17:18.537 --> 17:22.291
‐ Dan, you turned in a solid
steel weapon, a good profile.

17:22.291 --> 17:23.876
But unfortunately,
at the end of the day,

17:23.876 --> 17:25.503
it's the least finished.

17:25.503 --> 17:28.089
‐ I understand.
I understand.

17:28.089 --> 17:30.424
‐ Dan, please
surrender your blade.

17:30.424 --> 17:32.718
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

17:32.718 --> 17:35.388
‐ I had an amazing experience
and met amazing people.

17:35.388 --> 17:38.432
Like what part of that
is anything but awesome?

17:39.559 --> 17:41.227
<i>Learned a lot about forging</i>
<i>under pressure.</i>

17:41.227 --> 17:44.146
This is the most forging
pressure I've ever experienced.

17:44.146 --> 17:46.524
<i>I feel I can go on</i>
<i>and make anything.</i>

17:46.524 --> 17:48.693
But I learned
an incredible amount.

17:48.693 --> 17:50.528
<i>[dramatic musical sting]</i>

17:50.528 --> 17:52.697
‐ Bladesmiths, congratulations,

17:52.697 --> 17:54.031
you've made it
into the second round

17:54.031 --> 17:55.575
of this competition.

17:55.575 --> 17:57.118
And now that those blades
have been tempered,

17:57.118 --> 17:58.911
it's time to turn them into
fully functioning

17:58.911 --> 18:01.080
Fairbairn‐Sykes
fighting knives.

18:01.080 --> 18:02.748
You'll have to attach
a bronze handle,

18:02.748 --> 18:04.458
a guard, and a pommel

18:04.458 --> 18:06.836
in addition to address
any flaws and issues

18:06.836 --> 18:09.213
that were identified
in your blades in this round.

18:09.213 --> 18:10.798
You'll only have two hours

18:10.798 --> 18:12.883
in which to complete
all of your work.

18:12.883 --> 18:15.052
At the end of that time,
your blades will be tested

18:15.052 --> 18:18.639
for strength and durability
in a gas can stab...

18:18.639 --> 18:20.891
and for edge retention

18:20.891 --> 18:24.770
in a Kevlar‐reinforced
sandbag slice.

18:24.770 --> 18:26.230
Gentlemen, I remind you

18:26.230 --> 18:27.940
that after your blades
have been tested,

18:27.940 --> 18:29.900
one of you will be selected
to surrender your blade

18:29.900 --> 18:31.277
and leave The Forge.

18:31.277 --> 18:34.155
Good luck.
Your two hours starts now.

18:34.155 --> 18:35.781
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:35.781 --> 18:36.949
<i>‐ I've got to warp my blade.</i>

18:36.949 --> 18:38.451
I want to straighten that out

18:38.451 --> 18:39.994
so when it stabs
in the gas can,

18:39.994 --> 18:41.954
the forces are gonna be
basically in line.

18:41.954 --> 18:43.956
<i>That's gonna help</i>
<i>my blade perform.</i>

18:43.956 --> 18:45.791
‐ Elijah's got the
oxy‐acetylene torch.

18:45.791 --> 18:48.461
‐ It's gonna be really hard
to put enough softness

18:48.461 --> 18:50.338
in that blade
to straighten it out

18:50.338 --> 18:54.091
without overheating those edges
and losing your hardness.

18:54.091 --> 18:56.636
‐ I think I can heat

18:56.636 --> 18:58.846
<i>just the center of my blade</i>
<i>sufficiently</i>

18:58.846 --> 19:01.474
to take that warp out.

19:01.474 --> 19:03.809
‐ The part that concerns me
is Elijah's

19:03.809 --> 19:07.146
laying it on the edge of
the water bucket there

19:07.146 --> 19:08.814
and flexing it that way.

19:08.814 --> 19:10.775
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

19:10.775 --> 19:12.943
‐ There's a possibility
it could snap

19:12.943 --> 19:15.196
<i>or get bent even worse,</i>
<i>but I don't have a choice.</i>

19:15.196 --> 19:19.116
I've got a warp on my blade,
and I've got to fix it.

19:20.409 --> 19:23.245
<i>‐ Two hours isn't a lot of</i>
<i>time to get any handle done,</i>

19:23.245 --> 19:26.165
much less
a solid piece of bronze.

19:26.165 --> 19:29.210
‐ Now this bronze is
a pretty weighty material.

19:29.210 --> 19:30.711
We're talking about a weapon

19:30.711 --> 19:33.172
that weighs less than
1/2 pound.

19:33.172 --> 19:35.299
‐ And having five times
the weight

19:35.299 --> 19:37.551
on one end of it
doesn't help it.

19:37.551 --> 19:38.678
‐ Not at all.

19:38.678 --> 19:40.680
<i>‐ Fit up my handle.</i>

19:40.680 --> 19:42.515
<i>I got to take away</i>
<i>a little bit of material</i>

19:42.515 --> 19:45.184
'cause the judges did say
my tang was fat.

19:45.184 --> 19:48.187
‐ Austin's taken to heart
what we said about his tang,

19:48.187 --> 19:50.856
and he's thinning out
quite a bit.

19:50.856 --> 19:52.525
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:52.525 --> 19:55.027
‐ Got a lot to do, and I got
two hours to do it in.

19:55.027 --> 19:57.113
<i>Had to hollow ground it.</i>
<i>These folks said flat grind.</i>

19:57.113 --> 19:58.906
<i>My mistake.</i>

19:58.906 --> 20:01.200
<i>‐ Now, hollow grinds</i>
<i>seem to be so deep, in fact,</i>

20:01.200 --> 20:02.702
<i>that it's almost like</i>
<i>they get narrow</i>

20:02.702 --> 20:04.370
and flare back out
towards the edge.

20:04.370 --> 20:06.706
‐ Yep, they do, which is
actually a disadvantage,

20:06.706 --> 20:07.873
because if Richey
wants to make this

20:07.873 --> 20:09.875
more like the diamond profile,

20:09.875 --> 20:12.086
he can thin those edges out.
‐ Okay.

20:12.086 --> 20:14.088
‐ And that'll bring
some of that radius out.

20:14.088 --> 20:16.257
‐ In round one,
I didn't pay attention

20:16.257 --> 20:17.925
and I put the wrong grind
on the knife.

20:17.925 --> 20:19.927
<i>That leaves me more to do.</i>

20:19.927 --> 20:22.722
Worried if I can get
this done in two hours.

20:22.722 --> 20:24.890
<i>[rock music]</i>

20:24.890 --> 20:27.852
<i>‐ So the guard on this</i>
<i>Fairbairn‐Sykes combat blade,</i>

20:27.852 --> 20:30.563
it's there to keep your hand
from slipping onto the blade

20:30.563 --> 20:32.398
<i>when you're stabbing</i>
<i>your target.</i>

20:32.398 --> 20:34.400
<i>So I need to make it</i>
<i>big enough</i>

20:34.400 --> 20:36.694
<i>that it actually works</i>
<i>for what it's supposed to do</i>

20:36.694 --> 20:40.406
and then make it as close to
the original knife as possible.

20:40.406 --> 20:44.243
‐ And when you talk about
a simple and effective weapon,

20:44.243 --> 20:47.455
I think that this
F‐S fighting knife is it.

20:47.455 --> 20:49.039
‐ 70 years in service.

20:49.039 --> 20:51.542
‐ It's a cute little file.

20:51.542 --> 20:54.587
‐ Bladesmiths,
one hour has elapsed!

20:54.587 --> 20:56.464
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:56.464 --> 20:58.799
<i>‐ I made the pommel</i>
<i>out of the bronze.</i>

20:58.799 --> 21:01.051
<i>And now it's time to slap</i>
<i>my handle materials on</i>

21:01.051 --> 21:03.095
and attach them to the blade.

21:03.095 --> 21:06.432
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:06.432 --> 21:07.808
<i>I notice things are moving</i>

21:07.808 --> 21:09.602
<i>that aren't supposed to</i>
<i>be moving.</i>

21:09.602 --> 21:11.937
I look at that nut
that I put on there.

21:11.937 --> 21:13.272
<i>The threads broke</i>
<i>'cause I over‐tightened it.</i>

21:15.900 --> 21:17.109
leep] all of it.

21:17.109 --> 21:19.862
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:19.862 --> 21:22.406
That weld's gonna stick
to that nut, to the tang,

21:22.406 --> 21:24.533
and it's not
gonna move anywhere.

21:24.533 --> 21:25.993
<i>A stab into these jerrycans</i>

21:25.993 --> 21:27.745
<i>isn't just gonna test</i>
<i>the blade,</i>

21:27.745 --> 21:29.622
<i>it's gonna test the entire</i>
<i>handle construction.</i>

21:29.622 --> 21:30.956
So I don't want to be sent home

21:30.956 --> 21:32.792
because my pommel falls off.

21:32.792 --> 21:34.835
‐ Austin weld his nut on.

21:34.835 --> 21:37.129
Doesn't that negate
all the cross threading

21:37.129 --> 21:39.048
he was doing earlier
in round one?

21:39.048 --> 21:40.633
‐ Yeah, it negates that.

21:40.633 --> 21:43.260
The piece that he had threaded
on kind of got distorted.

21:43.260 --> 21:45.638
‐ Now is there a danger

21:45.638 --> 21:48.390
to welding
that nut as a pommel?

21:48.390 --> 21:50.851
‐ It's possible to bust
the weld, 'cause there's

21:50.851 --> 21:53.187
not a lot of material
there to weld them together

21:53.187 --> 21:56.482
and take that heat, so he
can break that weld loose.

21:56.482 --> 21:59.777
‐ I've got to make
a slotted cut in this handle

21:59.777 --> 22:01.821
right down next to the blade

22:01.821 --> 22:03.864
<i>because I've left</i>
<i>the tang wider.</i>

22:03.864 --> 22:05.908
‐ Almost like
it's keyed at the top.

22:05.908 --> 22:07.660
‐ Right.
‐ So he could key the tang

22:07.660 --> 22:10.496
at the top and keep the rest
of the tang round...

22:10.496 --> 22:12.164
‐ Right.
‐ And just worry about

22:12.164 --> 22:14.166
slotting the top of that.
‐ You have to set that lock

22:14.166 --> 22:17.253
into place on top.
‐ It's a good idea.

22:18.629 --> 22:21.841
Richey has that bronze
in his hand.

22:21.841 --> 22:24.260
It's not yet attached
to the tang.

22:24.260 --> 22:27.304
And he's shaping that bronze
before he puts it on the blade.

22:27.304 --> 22:30.349
‐ It's a really good idea
to shape the first 1 1/2 inch

22:30.349 --> 22:33.561
before you epoxy it into place,
'cause you're not gonna be able

22:33.561 --> 22:35.354
to get up close
to where the guard sits.

22:35.354 --> 22:38.941
<i>‐ This gonna take a while.</i>
<i>It's gonna be a job.</i>

22:39.942 --> 22:42.862
<i>‐ Pommel on this knife</i>
<i>is not large.</i>

22:42.862 --> 22:44.405
<i>It doesn't need to be.</i>

22:44.405 --> 22:46.282
And all it's there for is
to hold the handle on securely

22:46.282 --> 22:49.201
and provide a striking surface
if needed.

22:49.201 --> 22:51.704
‐ Elijah's going to weld
on some all‐thread.

22:51.704 --> 22:53.706
‐ Does he have
the guard on it now?

22:53.706 --> 22:56.292
Is that guard gonna fit over
that all‐thread?

22:56.292 --> 22:58.377
‐ Good question.

22:58.377 --> 23:00.087
‐ Oh, [bleep].

23:00.087 --> 23:04.216
<i>I forgot to slip my guard on</i>
<i>over the tang</i>

23:04.216 --> 23:06.886
<i>before I welded that thread</i>
<i>on there.</i>

23:06.886 --> 23:08.554
And now it doesn't fit.

23:08.554 --> 23:11.140
<i>Only thing I can do</i>
<i>is cut off the all‐thread,</i>

23:11.140 --> 23:12.766
<i>put my guard on,</i>
<i>and weld it back on.</i>

23:12.766 --> 23:14.393
So it's precious
minutes wasted.

23:14.393 --> 23:16.812
That was a great move.

23:16.812 --> 23:19.064
‐ 30 minutes, bladesmiths.

23:19.064 --> 23:21.317
<i>[energetic music]</i>

23:21.317 --> 23:24.278
‐ So it looks like Austin's
sharpening with 1/2 hour to go.

23:24.278 --> 23:26.322
‐ I'd really like to see him
work on that handle.

23:26.322 --> 23:27.865
The handle's pretty fat.

23:27.865 --> 23:29.241
<i>‐ For the gas can stab,</i>

23:29.241 --> 23:31.035
<i>I'm grinding my edge</i>
<i>accordingly.</i>

23:31.035 --> 23:32.453
<i>I want my tip</i>
<i>to have some meat to it,</i>

23:32.453 --> 23:35.331
but also I want it
to go through it.

23:35.331 --> 23:38.042
‐ I think Austin's handle's
gonna be way heavier

23:38.042 --> 23:40.502
than it needs to be,
but it's hard to get in

23:40.502 --> 23:43.380
underneath that guard
and taper that down.

23:43.380 --> 23:45.257
‐ That's all I can do to it.

23:45.257 --> 23:47.760
‐ Five minutes, bladesmiths.

23:47.760 --> 23:51.221
<i>‐ Got this all‐thread welded</i>
<i>on just a little bit crooked.</i>

23:51.221 --> 23:54.433
I don't see that
I have time to correct this.

23:54.433 --> 23:58.228
It's just gonna have a little
hole at the bottom of it.

23:58.228 --> 23:59.688
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:59.688 --> 24:01.315
<i>Sliding my handle on there,</i>

24:01.315 --> 24:03.233
<i>and it's not going all</i>
<i>the way up to the guard.</i>

24:03.233 --> 24:05.527
I'm gonna have to force it.

24:05.527 --> 24:06.946
‐ So we've got Richey over here

24:06.946 --> 24:08.572
kind of tapping things
together.

24:08.572 --> 24:10.115
The tip of the blade
is driven down

24:10.115 --> 24:12.785
into the wood
of his workstation there.

24:12.785 --> 24:16.246
‐ Oh, that's not good.
‐ Let's hope that tip's strong.

24:16.246 --> 24:17.581
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:17.581 --> 24:19.458
‐ Doing a pretest for you.
[laughs]

24:19.458 --> 24:21.961
‐ Hey, man.
Make it happen, captain.

24:21.961 --> 24:24.505
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:24.505 --> 24:28.467
‐ Five, four, three,

24:28.467 --> 24:29.969
two, one!

24:29.969 --> 24:33.472
Bladesmiths, this second round
of competition is over.

24:33.472 --> 24:35.641
<i>[dramatic chords]</i>
<i>‐ Round two's done.</i>

24:35.641 --> 24:37.059
Whoo!

24:37.059 --> 24:39.019
<i>I would love to make it</i>
<i>on to the next round.</i>

24:39.019 --> 24:43.357
It's gonna be a bear, might
as well be a grizzly, you know?

24:43.357 --> 24:46.610
‐ All right, bladesmiths,
welcome to the strength test,

24:46.610 --> 24:48.404
our gas can stab.

24:48.404 --> 24:51.156
I'm gonna take each
of your daggers

24:51.156 --> 24:53.325
and try to sabotage
these enemy gas cans.

24:53.325 --> 24:55.661
It's gonna test the overall
construction of your knife

24:55.661 --> 24:57.037
as well as your heat treat.

24:57.037 --> 24:58.706
Richey, you're up first.
How you feeling?

24:58.706 --> 25:00.833
‐ Ha. Big swing, J.

25:02.167 --> 25:03.752
<i>I'm really worried</i>
<i>about my tip</i>

25:03.752 --> 25:06.964
<i>because I had a real,</i>
<i>real fine tip on there.</i>

25:06.964 --> 25:10.676
I know J.‐‐he really puts
a test on the knife.

25:10.676 --> 25:13.345
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

25:13.345 --> 25:15.681
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:15.681 --> 25:17.516
‐ [grunts]
Ugh!

25:17.516 --> 25:19.977
Ugh! Uhh!

25:19.977 --> 25:23.897
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:23.897 --> 25:26.150
[grunting]
Uhh! Uhh.

25:26.150 --> 25:29.028
<i>[intense musical buildup]</i>

25:29.028 --> 25:30.571
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:30.571 --> 25:32.156
‐ Whew.
[chuckles]

25:32.156 --> 25:35.701
‐ Good job, Richey.
Your blade held up good.

25:35.701 --> 25:37.536
You lost just
a hair of the tip.

25:37.536 --> 25:40.164
You handle's out of alignment
from the blade a little bit.

25:40.164 --> 25:42.541
So a couple of those stabs,
when I went down,

25:42.541 --> 25:44.793
it kind of torqued a bit.

25:44.793 --> 25:47.963
But got no chips, no rolls.
Everything's strong.

25:47.963 --> 25:50.507
Good job.
‐ Thank you. Thank you.

25:50.507 --> 25:52.760
‐ Okay, Elijah, after seeing
that, how do you feel?

25:52.760 --> 25:57.056
‐ A little nervous,
but...it is what it is.

25:57.056 --> 26:00.726
<i>I'm worried that the edges</i>
<i>of my blade</i>

26:00.726 --> 26:02.144
<i>lost a little bit of hardness</i>

26:02.144 --> 26:04.021
<i>when I was working</i>
<i>the warp out.</i>

26:04.021 --> 26:06.523
So I'm hoping that there's
enough edge retention there

26:06.523 --> 26:07.816
to perform well.

26:07.816 --> 26:10.069
<i>[dramatic descending chords]</i>

26:10.069 --> 26:12.571
‐ [grunts]
Uhh!

26:12.571 --> 26:14.948
Uhh. Uhh!

26:14.948 --> 26:16.575
Uhh!

26:16.575 --> 26:19.745
<i>[rock music]</i>

26:19.745 --> 26:26.168
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:26.168 --> 26:28.879
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

26:28.879 --> 26:31.965
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:31.965 --> 26:33.842
‐ Elijah, good job.
You still have an edge.

26:33.842 --> 26:36.595
Everything's still tight.
Overall, nicely done.

26:36.595 --> 26:37.971
‐ Thank you.

26:37.971 --> 26:40.849
‐ And then there was one.
[laughter]

26:40.849 --> 26:42.476
How you doing?
‐ I'm doing pretty good.

26:42.476 --> 26:45.104
‐ Let's see if your knife
does the same thing.

26:46.105 --> 26:48.649
<i>‐ I know J.</i>
<i>doesn't hold back at all,</i>

26:48.649 --> 26:51.360
<i>and my blade</i>
<i>could break in half.</i>

26:52.778 --> 26:55.989
My tip could just roll over
and not stab the cans at all.

26:55.989 --> 26:57.950
I'm pretty nervous.

26:57.950 --> 26:59.910
‐ [grunting] Uhh!

26:59.910 --> 27:01.286
Uhh!

27:01.286 --> 27:04.289
<i>[hard rock music]</i>

27:04.289 --> 27:05.874
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:05.874 --> 27:06.750
‐ Oh ho ho.

27:09.795 --> 27:11.672
‐ [groans] Uh‐oh. <i>chords]</i>

27:11.672 --> 27:14.967
<i>[dramatic chords]</i>

27:14.967 --> 27:16.552
‐ All right, Austin,
we obviously

27:16.552 --> 27:18.262
have a problem here.
‐ Yeah.

27:18.262 --> 27:19.638
‐ The heat treat‐‐
there was an issue.

27:19.638 --> 27:21.348
You can probably see
from there,

27:21.348 --> 27:23.100
your grain structure‐‐
it's very coarse.

27:23.100 --> 27:24.852
The other thing
working against you

27:24.852 --> 27:26.478
was the weight of this handle.

27:26.478 --> 27:29.356
Having this much weight
coming in behind this blade

27:29.356 --> 27:32.150
with a brittle heat
treat on it‐‐

27:32.150 --> 27:34.444
we just lost it.

27:34.444 --> 27:37.406
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

27:37.406 --> 27:39.908
‐ Austin, your blade has
suffered a catastrophic failure

27:39.908 --> 27:41.785
in the middle
of our strength test.

27:41.785 --> 27:45.205
For that reason, we have to ask
you to please leave The Forge.

27:45.205 --> 27:47.082
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:47.082 --> 27:49.877
‐ I'm not ashamed of what
I did here today.

27:49.877 --> 27:51.587
I overcame a lot of challenges.

27:51.587 --> 27:54.631
And it's not gonna stop me.
I'm just gonna keep growing.

27:54.631 --> 27:57.092
This has taught me that,
you know, never stop learning,

27:57.092 --> 27:59.177
always push for better.

27:59.177 --> 28:01.346
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:01.346 --> 28:03.640
‐ Richey,
Elijah, congratulations.

28:03.640 --> 28:05.183
You guys have made it
to the final round

28:05.183 --> 28:07.227
of this competition.
Now, when you came here,

28:07.227 --> 28:10.647
we had you forge
an iconic dagger from history.

28:10.647 --> 28:14.026
Now we're sending you back
to recreate this weapon.

28:14.026 --> 28:16.236
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:16.236 --> 28:18.488
General Yamashita's gunto.

28:20.365 --> 28:24.244
<i>Made by famed swordsmith</i>
<i>Fujiwara Kanenaga</i>

28:24.244 --> 28:25.787
<i>in the 17th century,</i>

28:25.787 --> 28:28.081
<i>this katana‐style blade</i>
<i>accompanied Japan's</i>

28:28.081 --> 28:30.250
<i>revered</i>
<i>General Tomoyuki Yamashita</i>

28:30.250 --> 28:32.252
<i>as he led troops</i>
<i>in the invasion of Singapore</i>

28:32.252 --> 28:34.588
<i>and Malaya</i>
<i>during World War II.</i>

28:34.588 --> 28:37.841
<i>The traditionally curved sword</i>
<i>is adorned with tassels.</i>

28:37.841 --> 28:39.593
<i>This represented</i>
<i>the rank of general</i>

28:39.593 --> 28:41.595
<i>and indicated</i>
<i>that it was primarily used</i>

28:41.595 --> 28:43.430
<i>for ceremony</i>
<i>and in not battle.</i>

28:43.430 --> 28:46.099
<i>The general's legacy</i>
<i>continues as the sword rests</i>

28:46.099 --> 28:49.061
<i>as a prized artifact</i>
<i>in the West Point Museum</i>

28:49.061 --> 28:51.521
<i>and also through the legend of</i>
<i>his plundered gold treasures</i>

28:51.521 --> 28:54.232
<i>said to be hidden in caves</i>
<i>and tunnels of the Philippines</i>

28:54.232 --> 29:00.113
<i>as seen in the History series</i>
<i>"Lost Gold of World War II."</i>

29:00.113 --> 29:01.323
The length of the blade,

29:01.323 --> 29:03.533
as measured from the habaki
the tip,

29:03.533 --> 29:06.161
must be between
28 and 29 inches.

29:06.161 --> 29:08.080
You must have
a tsuba‐style guard,

29:08.080 --> 29:12.000
a traditionally wrapped tsuka
handle with a sword knot ring.

29:12.000 --> 29:13.669
And you must have a sword knot

29:13.669 --> 29:15.462
that is no more
than 6 inches in length

29:15.462 --> 29:18.882
as measured from the ring
to the end of the tassel.

29:18.882 --> 29:21.677
‐ A Japanese samurai sword...
[laughs]

29:21.677 --> 29:23.428
<i>with a tassel on it.</i>

29:23.428 --> 29:26.014
I was six years old before
I learned to tie my shoes.

29:26.014 --> 29:28.308
Now I gotta go home
and lace up a sword handle.

29:28.308 --> 29:30.060
‐ You'll have four days
at your home forges

29:30.060 --> 29:31.895
in which to complete
all these parameters

29:31.895 --> 29:35.148
before delivering your weapon
to our panel of expert judges.

29:35.148 --> 29:36.984
Only after they
thoroughly tested them

29:36.984 --> 29:38.944
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

29:38.944 --> 29:40.946
who leaves here
with a check for 10 grand.

29:40.946 --> 29:43.115
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in four days.

29:43.115 --> 29:45.742
‐ Thank you.
Good luck.

29:46.660 --> 29:48.829
<i>‐ Doing this challenge</i>
<i>at my home forge,</i>

29:48.829 --> 29:51.456
<i>it'll be good</i>
<i>'cause I'm in my own space.</i>

29:51.456 --> 29:54.084
<i>I will be missing</i>
<i>some of the tools</i>

29:54.084 --> 29:55.669
at the judges' forge for sure.

29:55.669 --> 29:57.796
This gunto is a little bit
more of a challenge.

29:57.796 --> 30:00.298
<i>My equipment</i>
<i>is not conducive</i>

30:00.298 --> 30:03.844
<i>to working with</i>
<i>longer blades.</i>

30:03.844 --> 30:08.015
This is how you get a full
heat on a little forge

30:08.015 --> 30:11.560
with a long blade‐‐
you do this a lot.

30:11.560 --> 30:13.979
I have not made a katana
or a gunto before.

30:13.979 --> 30:15.981
<i>I think the biggest thing</i>
<i>that I'm struggling with</i>

30:15.981 --> 30:18.608
<i>is just getting the right</i>
<i>curvature in the blade.</i>

30:18.608 --> 30:22.070
But that's part of making
a particular blade

30:22.070 --> 30:23.947
for the first time.

30:23.947 --> 30:26.992
<i>It's quite a process.</i>

30:28.744 --> 30:31.496
<i>‐ It's day one, I'm back</i>
<i>here in my home forge.</i>

30:31.496 --> 30:36.710
I'm gonna make a Yamashuto
gunto‐‐gun‐to.

30:36.710 --> 30:38.170
[laughing]

30:38.170 --> 30:40.881
A Japanese sword.

30:40.881 --> 30:42.466
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:42.466 --> 30:45.886
Hopefully, by the end of today,
I've got my forging done.

30:45.886 --> 30:49.306
What I'm gonna to do is keep
a thick spine right in here,

30:49.306 --> 30:51.349
get a taper from here to here.

30:51.349 --> 30:53.935
I got to get that
right curve on that thing.

30:53.935 --> 30:55.562
Got to...

30:55.562 --> 30:57.731
Ha. Get it to do that.

30:59.149 --> 31:01.318
‐ Trying to maximize my heat.

31:01.318 --> 31:04.279
Um, this is not ideal...

31:04.279 --> 31:06.156
‐ Daddy?
‐ For getting this whole blade

31:06.156 --> 31:08.283
heated up.
‐ Where's my little knife‐‐

31:08.283 --> 31:11.078
‐ I don't know
where you left your little

31:11.078 --> 31:13.747
dull‐bladed knife.
That's a toy.

31:13.747 --> 31:15.373
This is what I do for a living.

31:15.373 --> 31:19.669
This is how I feed my kids
and myself and my wife.

31:19.669 --> 31:22.130
<i>Today, I need to do</i>
<i>some grinding</i>

31:22.130 --> 31:24.758
<i>and get heat treat finished.</i>

31:24.758 --> 31:28.637
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:28.637 --> 31:33.683
The steel settled into
a rather un‐straight manner.

31:33.683 --> 31:36.770
I think that's an easier way
to break a blade

31:36.770 --> 31:40.690
is applying more force
than you should have to.

31:41.483 --> 31:43.235
Yeah,
that ain't coming out.

31:43.235 --> 31:46.947
I have to reheat this back up
and then re‐quench it.

31:46.947 --> 31:48.323
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:48.323 --> 31:50.117
<i>When you heat steel up</i>
<i>that hot,</i>

31:50.117 --> 31:52.744
<i>you're enlarging</i>
<i>the grain structure.</i>

31:52.744 --> 31:55.914
<i>Worst‐case scenario,</i>
<i>you're gonna ruin the steel.</i>

31:56.957 --> 31:59.584
Ooh.
Never had that happen before.

31:59.584 --> 32:01.419
Think I hit the bottom.

32:01.419 --> 32:03.630
It's better than last time.

32:03.630 --> 32:05.090
After the second quench,

32:05.090 --> 32:08.802
I was probably able
to get it straight‐ish.

32:08.802 --> 32:13.098
Stay. Just stay.
Don't do anything.

32:13.098 --> 32:14.808
<i>[rock music]</i>

32:14.808 --> 32:18.061
<i>‐ My goal for today</i>
<i>is to build me a quench a tank</i>

32:18.061 --> 32:20.814
and then go into
my heat treatin' process.

32:20.814 --> 32:22.649
<i>My plan for making</i>
<i>a quench tank‐‐</i>

32:22.649 --> 32:29.281
I've got an old fiberglass tank
that is for cleaning guns.

32:29.281 --> 32:30.991
That'll work.

32:30.991 --> 32:33.994
<i>[intense music]</i>

32:33.994 --> 32:37.664
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:40.083 --> 32:42.085
<i>We got it pretty good</i>
<i>fired up,</i>

32:42.085 --> 32:45.672
But I've got to get this blade
hard and get it in the clamp.

32:45.672 --> 32:48.049
We'll worry about the shop
burnin' down right here.

32:48.049 --> 32:49.843
We got to get this fire out.

32:49.843 --> 32:53.096
Oh, Lord!
Get the fire extinguisher.

32:53.096 --> 32:56.141
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

32:56.141 --> 32:57.601
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:57.601 --> 32:59.186
Lord have mercy.

32:59.186 --> 33:01.938
Might oughta
to call somebody.

33:03.815 --> 33:05.483
<i>We got it pretty good</i>
<i>[dr fired up. r</i>

33:05.483 --> 33:07.444
We gotta get this fire out.

33:07.444 --> 33:10.197
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

33:10.197 --> 33:13.783
Man. Thank You, Lord.
We could have had a disaster.

33:13.783 --> 33:17.162
A word to the wise
is sufficient.

33:17.162 --> 33:19.998
Use metal, use something
that won't catch fire.

33:19.998 --> 33:22.667
And fiberglass will catch fire.

33:22.667 --> 33:24.336
<i>When I take the blade</i>
<i>out of the clamps,</i>

33:24.336 --> 33:26.922
<i>and she's straight as a hair.</i>

33:26.922 --> 33:28.840
Hoo! I'm proud of that.

33:28.840 --> 33:31.343
We get
the smoke out of shop,

33:31.343 --> 33:34.346
we'll gonna proceed
with firing it.

33:34.346 --> 33:36.848
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:36.848 --> 33:39.184
‐ It is day three, and today,
I'm working on

33:39.184 --> 33:42.020
<i>the habaki and the guard.</i>

33:42.020 --> 33:43.730
Basically,
the way you make a habaki

33:43.730 --> 33:46.983
is your blade goes here
and the sides basically fold up

33:46.983 --> 33:50.195
and you put it together,
solder it together.

33:50.195 --> 33:52.030
Yay, habaki!

33:52.030 --> 33:54.366
Tomorrow,
I have to shape the handle,

33:54.366 --> 33:56.201
<i>and then I have</i>
<i>to wrap the handle.</i>

33:56.201 --> 33:58.662
It's lots of fit and finish.

34:00.497 --> 34:04.209
‐ The last day. Hurray.

34:04.209 --> 34:06.253
<i>I've got this wrap started.</i>

34:06.253 --> 34:08.880
<i>Surprisingly,</i>
<i>it's going pretty good.</i>

34:08.880 --> 34:10.924
<i>Tell you what, "Forged in</i>
<i>Fire" teach you some stuff.</i>

34:10.924 --> 34:14.636
So far, I've been a blacksmith,
a bladesmith,

34:14.636 --> 34:16.554
a seamstress,
and a firefighter.

34:16.554 --> 34:17.889
[laughing]

34:18.974 --> 34:22.227
This took a lot more grit
than I ever imagined.

34:22.227 --> 34:24.271
<i>I knew it would be tough,</i>
<i>but I didn't know</i>

34:24.271 --> 34:27.399
it was gonna be this tough,
and I can't wait to see Doug

34:27.399 --> 34:29.567
cut a Billy goat in two
or something.

34:29.567 --> 34:31.569
<i>[laughing]</i>

34:31.569 --> 34:34.531
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

34:34.531 --> 34:37.075
‐ Richey, Elijah,
welcome back to The Forge.

34:37.075 --> 34:40.537
You fellas have had four days
to work on your working version

34:40.537 --> 34:44.457
of the infamous
General Yamashita's gunto.

34:44.457 --> 34:46.001
Richey, how did it go for you?

34:46.001 --> 34:47.585
‐ I had a little shop fire,

34:47.585 --> 34:50.338
but we got her put out
and went right on to work.

34:51.423 --> 34:55.218
<i>Got a 5160 blade.</i>
<i>The handle is curly maple,</i>

34:55.218 --> 34:56.803
<i>and, of course,</i>
<i>brass hand guard</i>

